{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1783586034,"nonce":"XH7DsnsOZqnxRT4eMOPw69KcJbc=","title":"The runtime query render path (`to_sql()` and the prepared/params renderers) is infallible: it","message":"returns a `String` and `.unwrap()`s the internal `io::Result`. That was safe while runtime query\nrendering never produced a *semantic* reject — runtime-query invalidity is normally gated at\nCOMPILE time via marker traits (`SupportsIntersectExceptAll`, `SupportsReturning`, …), so the\nrender itself could only fail on a (never-triggered) non-UTF-8 writer guard.\n\nPR 2.0d (CTE render unification) introduced the first semantic reject reachable from `to_sql()`:\na **recursive CTE whose arm carries its own `ORDER BY`/`LIMIT`/`OFFSET`** has no valid rendering on\nSQLite (SQLite's recursive-CTE grammar forbids a parenthesized arm, which is the only way to scope\none). The shared renderer returns `ErrorKind::Unsupported`; the runtime query path unwraps it, so\nsuch a SQLite query **panics** in `to_sql()` (repro: a `RecursiveCteDefinition` whose anchor is\n`db.from::\u003cT\u003e()…​.order_by(…).limit(n).project(…)`, queried via `Sqlite`).\n\nThis shape was already non-functional on SQLite before 2.0d (it rendered invalid parenthesized SQL\nthat SQLite rejected at execution), and it is rare + semantically dubious — but a render-time panic\nis a worse failure mode than a returned error. The fallible VIEW/DDL path already rejects it cleanly\n(`render_create_view`/`render_plan` return the error).\n\n\nPlumb a fallible runtime render through the query/execution APIs so the reject propagates as a clean\nerror instead of a panic:\n- add a fallible variant (e.g. `try_to_sql() -\u003e Result\u003cString, _\u003e`) alongside `to_sql()` across every\n  backend's query objects, or make the render entry points return the error;\n- surface the render error through the execution path (execute/prepare) rather than unwrapping;\n- replace the `write_cte_prefix(...).unwrap()` sites in `squealy/src/render.rs` (and the\n  `squealy-test` equivalent) with propagation;\n- keep `to_sql()`'s ergonomic infallible form where the shape is statically known-renderable, or\n  document that it panics on an unrenderable dynamic CTE shape.\n\nThen remove the interim SQLite-scoped-arm limitation note on `RecursiveCteDefinition` (added in 2.0d).\n\n\n`RecursiveCteDefinition` carries a `# SQLite limitation` doc note describing the panic; the\n`Dialect::supports_parenthesized_recursive_cte_arm` seam (default true; SQLite false) governs the\nreject. A scoped recursive arm renders parenthesized on PostgreSQL/MySQL.","files":null}]}